`crates/ctx-status/src` implements the `ctx-status` binary: a CLI that maintains `docs/status.json` as the sole source of truth for a task backlog and regenerates `docs/STATUS.md` from it. Depending on this crate as a binary gets you four operations â€” `list`, `add-task`, `migrate`, `render` â€” all going through the same `Fs` trait seam, so behavior is identical whether run against real disk (`StdFs`) or a `FakeFs` in tests.

The core coupling: `model::priority_sorted` (impact highâ†’low, then difficulty easyâ†’hard) is the single sort used by both `render.rs` and `runner.rs`'s `list`/`save`, and `render.rs`'s markdown output is deterministic, so any change to sort order or row rendering must be validated against both the JSON store shape and the markdown table format shared with `ctx_core::status_table` (also used by `ctx-brief` â€” coordinate schema changes there). `runner.rs`'s `save()` is the only path that writes both files, guaranteeing STATUS.md never lags status.json except during manual edits, which `render` catches up.

Layering: `main.rs` wires `StdFs` and handles the `--contract` bypass; `cli.rs` parses argv and dispatches; `runner.rs`/`runner/` do the real orchestration (load/validate/append/save); `model.rs` and `render.rs` are pure, filesystem-free logic; `error.rs` defines the shared error taxonomy every layer surfaces unchanged; `fs.rs` is the disk abstraction; `contract.rs` is the docs-mirrored contract string that must stay in sync with `CLAUDE.md`/`README.md`. A typical schema change (new task field) touches `model.rs`, `runner.rs`'s `add_task`, `render.rs`, and the shared `ctx_core::status_table` together.

Invariant across the subtree: impact/difficulty values are validated once at `add_task` time (`normalize_impact`/`normalize_difficulty`), so every other component can assume stored rows are already canonical.